{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D2, fourth-best from your longest suit — the standard start against 3NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks. The suit that decides this hand is clubs: dummy's \CA-J-T-2 over your 6-4, missing BOTH the king and the queen. That calls for a DOUBLE FINESSE: lead toward dummy twice — the ten first, the jack later. You expect to lose one of the two, but roughly three times in four at least one hook wins, and that extra club trick is your ninth. Plan for one club loser, not two.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \D2 to dummy's king. Now go right after clubs: low toward dummy's ten — it loses to East's queen. One down, as expected; do not lose heart. Regain the lead and play a second club toward dummy, inserting the jack — it HOLDS, riding through West's king. Cash the \CA and the king falls too: two club winners, one loser, mission accomplished. With the top hearts, the diamonds behind dummy's A-K-J, and the \SA, nine tricks are home.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Missing the king AND queen, one finesse is a coin flip — but two finesses are a heavy favorite: about three chances in four that one of them wins. You hooked the ten, lost to the queen, hooked the jack, and won through the king. Losing the first round was part of the plan, and the second hook paid for it. Well played.}
